A most concise, library-free, Java 7+ variant:
```java
public static void unzip(InputStream is, Path targetDir) throws IOException {
    targetDir = targetDir.toAbsolutePath();
    try (ZipInputStream zipIn = new ZipInputStream(is)) {
        for (ZipEntry ze; (ze = zipIn.getNextEntry()) != null; ) {
            Path resolvedPath = targetDir.resolve(ze.getName()).normalize();
            if (!resolvedPath.startsWith(targetDir)) {
                // see: https://snyk.io/research/zip-slip-vulnerability
                throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Entry with an illegal path: &quot; 
                        + ze.getName());
            }
            if (ze.isDirectory()) {
                Files.createDirectories(resolvedPath);
            } else {
                Files.createDirectories(resolvedPath.getParent());
                Files.copy(zipIn, resolvedPath);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

The `createDirectories` is needed in both branches because zip files not always contain all the parent directories as a separate entries, but might contain them only to represent empty directories.

The code addresses the [ZIP-slip vulnerability][1], it fails if some ZIP entry would go outside of the `targetDir`. Such ZIPs are not created using the usual tools and are very likely hand-crafted to exploit the vulnerability.


  [1]: https://snyk.io/research/zip-slip-vulnerability

