Try tracking the level of nesting:

    public class Javagony
    {
        public static void main(String[] args)
        {
            loop(0);
        }
    
        static int n = 1;
    
        public static void loop(int l)
        {
            System.out.println(l+&quot;:&quot;+n);
            n++;
            try
            {
                loop(l+1);
            }
            catch (StackOverflowError _e)
            {
                loop(l+1);
            }
        }
    }

it&#39;s not getting any further in the recursion and using up more stack, trying to do so generates the exception again. When it reaches the limit, the code sort of flails around in place.

So no, catching the exception does not allow you to use more stack space than the limit. The recommendation against catching it comes from the assumption that you are unlikely to have a sensible way of recovering from this condition.

